        title: "City Pop Crystallizes",
        body: "By 1985 City Pop is no longer an experimental genre searching for its identity — it is the fully matured sound of urban Japan, with settled conventions, a trained audience, and a production infrastructure capable of executing its aesthetic ambitions at consistent professional quality. The genre's roots run back to the early 1970s, when musicians influenced by American soft rock, jazz-funk, and soul began filtering those influences through Japanese sensibility. By the time of Tatsuro Yamashita's Sugar Babe project (1973–1975) and through his solo catalog at RCA Japan and Moon Records in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the genre's harmonic language and production philosophy are clearly established.\n\nChristmas Eve, the third track on Yamashita's Melodies album released in November 1983, crystallizes what City Pop means at its most polished. The song's combination of steel-drum melody, multilayered vocal harmonies, and precisely engineered intimacy makes it the ideal FM listening experience. By the winter of 1985, its annual return to radio rotation has already acquired the character of a seasonal institution. Listeners who bought the album in 1983 hear the song now as a familiar fixture; listeners who discover it through radio in 1985 encounter it as something already traditional. This compressed cultural lifecycle — two years from release to ritual — demonstrates the speed at which prosperity, great production, and consistent FM distribution can transform a well-crafted song into a shared experience.\n\nThe genre's characteristic elements are fully assembled by 1985. Jazz-funk rhythm sections form the foundation. The Yamaha DX7, which arrived in Japanese studios in 1983 and rapidly became standard equipment, supplies synthesizer warmth — its electric piano patch creates the soft-keyboard texture that runs through nearly every City Pop production of the period. Lyrics inhabit an aspirational urban geography: coastal drives, Tokyo at night, emotional lives conducted against backdrops of prosperity and leisure. FM radio's fidelity advantages over AM reward complex productions, and the quality stereo equipment entering Japanese urban households turns production investment into audible listener experience. The genre and its delivery infrastructure have matured in parallel.",
