        title: "FM Radio as Cultural Infrastructure",
        body: "FM broadcasting in Japan develops its national infrastructure through the 1970s — NHK-FM in operation since 1969, Tokyo FM launching in 1970, FM Osaka in 1970, FM Aichi in 1972, and additions continuing through the late 1970s and early 1980s. By 1985 FM radio has established itself as the dominant medium for sophisticated popular music, and City Pop — whose production investments are designed to be audible through high-fidelity reproduction — is its ideal programming content.\n\nThe technical argument for FM is specific and measurable: frequency modulation broadcasts in stereo with a frequency response extending to 15 kHz, a signal-to-noise ratio significantly superior to AM, and a dynamic range that reveals the precise spatial placement of instruments across the stereo field. A City Pop record mixed with care — bass centered and tight, vocal slightly forward, synthesizer pads spread across the stereo image, reverb tails that suggest space without obscuring detail — sounds like a qualitatively different object through FM than through AM. This is audible to anyone comparing the same recording through both formats on quality equipment.\n\nSony, Kenwood, Denon, and Pioneer are manufacturing FM tuners and integrated amplifiers at prices that rising bubble-era salaries are beginning to make accessible to young urban professional households. The aspirational purchase of a quality stereo system in 1985 creates a home listening environment in which the City Pop producer's investment is properly received. The equipment manufacturer needs FM content that demonstrates the value of quality reproduction; the label needs a broadcast medium that justifies production investment; the radio station needs music that keeps technically-minded listeners tuned in. City Pop sits at the intersection of all three needs.\n\nLate-night FM programming — Tokyo FM's Between-a-Rock and equivalent weekend evening programs that run from nine through midnight — is the specific delivery vehicle. The programming model uses disc jockeys with genuine musical knowledge to curate extended sets of domestic and imported music with minimal commercial interruption. The late-night FM show is not incidental to City Pop's distribution; it is central to it. The listener who stays awake to hear it is precisely the listener the music is made for: urban, attentive, willing to invest in quality, and with enough disposable income to buy the album the following day.",
