        title: "Taeko Ohnuki and Sophistication",
        body: "Taeko Ohnuki's professional career begins alongside Tatsuro Yamashita in Sugar Babe — the two were musical collaborators before either had a solo career — and her subsequent development as a solo artist charts the most intellectually demanding path within City Pop's range. Her debut album Sunshower, released in 1977 and produced by Haruomi Hosono, establishes the reference points that define her work throughout the 1980s: bossa nova rhythm, French pop harmonic language, an arrangement sensibility that values elegance and economy over warmth and richness. Her 1980 album Romantique deepens the French influence further, incorporating string arrangements and a production aesthetic that references Serge Gainsbourg-era French pop more than American R&B.\n\nWhere Yamashita absorbs American soul through a Japanese sensibility, Ohnuki absorbs French chanson and European chamber pop — a meaningfully different set of sources producing a meaningfully different kind of music. The harmonic vocabulary of her work employs extended chords and modal passages that require a listener comfortable with ambiguity. The emotional register is refined and slightly cool, where Yamashita's is warm and direct. Her audience in the mid-1980s numbers perhaps 50,000 to 80,000 buyers per album cycle — not large by the standards of the domestic charts — but it is among the most culturally influential consumer segments in Japanese music: art directors, fashion designers, musicians, and educated urban professionals whose taste shapes what the mainstream eventually finds acceptable.\n\nThe bubble economy's A-and-R culture supports Ohnuki's career in 1986 because the financial logic of her releases is sustainable when borrowing costs are low. A label willing to invest in her fourth or fifth album does so against the expectation of a modest but reliable return from a loyal audience, plus the reputational value of maintaining a prestigious critical artist on the roster. In a tighter industry, this calculation fails: the modest return does not justify the investment cost. In 1986, it does. Ohnuki's continued career is one of the bubble economy's more indirect cultural gifts — made possible not by extravagant spending but by the changed financial arithmetic that makes modest-return investment viable.",
