        body: "The scale and sophistication of live music production in Japan escalates noticeably through 1987, and City Pop artists are among the primary beneficiaries of this escalation. Corporate entertainment spending — a budget category that has been expanding across the bubble years and whose 1987 allocation is at a peak — flows into the concert industry through multiple channels: corporate block ticket purchases for client entertainment, tour sponsorships by companies seeking premium brand associations, and venue investments funded by real estate and entertainment companies whose asset appreciation has generated unprecedented development capital.\n\nThe physical venues available for major concerts are improving. Nakano Sun Plaza (capacity 2,222, opened 1973) and the Budokan remain primary Tokyo venues, but the broader touring circuit is expanding. Sound system investment is particularly consequential for City Pop's live presentation. The genre's studio productions are made with spatial complexity — instruments positioned precisely in the stereo field, reverbs designed to suggest room acoustics, arrangements that require clean separation to be intelligible. A poor-quality sound system in a concert venue renders this complexity as mud. The Meyer Sound and JBL professional arrays being installed in major Japanese venues in the mid-1980s have sufficient resolution to reproduce this complexity in real-time for a live audience. The concert can now attempt to deliver, in a physical space, what the studio recording promises on headphones.\n\nStage design and lighting are also professionalizing rapidly. Concert directors with backgrounds in theater design and commercial art direction are brought into productions whose visual presentation had previously been managed by touring crew without specialist expertise. The result — coordinated lighting states, purpose-built scenic elements, a visual language for each artist's performance that supports rather than contradicts their recorded aesthetic — treats the concert as a designed object rather than merely a performance. This level of production investment is only viable when corporate entertainment budgets create a market for premium concert experiences, and in 1987 those budgets are at their maximum.",
