        title: "The Year of Maximum Production",
        body: "1988 represents City Pop production at its absolute maximum across every measurable dimension. The economic conditions that enable this peak are fully established and mutually reinforcing: the Bank of Japan's discount rate sits at 2.5%, the Nikkei has crossed 25,000 yen on its way toward 30,000, land prices in major urban areas have been appreciating for two years, and the wealth effect is generating consumer confidence that extends to entertainment spending in every category. Label executives who approved cautious budgets in 1984 are approving ambitious ones in 1988, because four years of financial history have consistently rewarded ambition.\n\nThe physical environment of Tokyo's professional recording studios in 1988 represents the convergence of the best available analog technology with early professional digital processing. Studios at the top of the market — Victor Studio in Aoyama, Onkio Haus in Akasaka, Sound City in Minami-Aoyama — are equipped with Neve and SSL mixing consoles, Lexicon 480L digital reverbs, and outboard processing chains comparable to the best American facilities. The 24-track analog tape format remains standard for tracking, with Studer machines maintaining the warmth that characterizes the era's productions. Digital mastering — allowing precise equalization and limiting before disc cutting — is standard practice.\n\nThe average production budget for a major-label City Pop album in 1988 is difficult to document precisely, but industry practice of the period suggests per-album costs of 20 to 50 million yen for fully realized productions — covering session fees, studio time, arrangement costs, and mixing. These budgets assume sales of 50,000 to 100,000 units before profit begins. The label accepts this breakeven horizon because the track record of similar investments over the preceding four years has been positive, because the consumer market is expanding, and because the alternative — investing less and producing something demonstrably inferior — carries its own commercial risk in a market where listeners can hear the difference. The music this environment produces carries a specific quality: confidence without anxiety, sophistication without self-consciousness. Albums made in 1988 sound like work produced by people who know exactly what they are doing, with sufficient resources to do it fully, in conditions they expect to continue indefinitely.",
