        title: "The Collector Market's Inertia",
        body: "The anime collector market's response to the economic contraction of 1990 follows a pattern that the industry can observe in real-time through retail sales data: it contracts more slowly than the general consumer entertainment market, because the motivations sustaining it are more deeply embedded in identity and habit than the casual consumer's relationship to entertainment spending. The Gundam model kit collector who has been building and purchasing since the original 1979 series does not stop because the Nikkei falls thirty-nine percent; their collection is partially assembled and the investment in assembling it — of time, money, and identity — provides its own momentum toward continuation.\n\nThe otaku consumer — a term acquiring more precise definition in 1990 through Akihabara retail culture and the developing discourse of dedicated anime fandom — is buying for reasons more deeply embedded in identity than any casual observer's framework for understanding entertainment spending would suggest. The collection is not a product; it is a life project. Individual purchase decisions within it are not primarily calculated against alternative uses of money; they are continuations of an ongoing commitment. This makes the collector market structurally stickier than the general consumer entertainment market.\n\nThe practical consequence for the anime industry is that the contracted market of 1990 and 1991 is smaller but more demographically concentrated than the peak-bubble market was. The casual consumer who spent on anime merchandise and OVAs in 1988 because the bubble's prosperity made entertainment spending feel low-cost has contracted. What remains is the dedicated collector whose purchasing is habitual and identity-attached. Producing for this audience requires different creative and commercial calculations — more franchise extension, more series completion, less original creative content aimed at general audiences. The industry adjusts its production slate accordingly, not by policy decision but by the accumulation of individual greenlight decisions made under changed financial circumstances.",
