        title: "Harajuku and the Street",
        body: "The Harajuku pedestrian paradise — Hokoten, short for Hokousha tengoku — begins in 1977 on the broad tree-lined avenue of Omotesando, and by 1985 has become the most photographed fashion location in Asia. Each Sunday, the stretch of road closes to vehicles, and the space fills with teenagers who have spent the week constructing wardrobes and identities for this specific public performance. The fashion is not primarily commercial — it is expressive, assemblage-based, drawing on subcultural reference points rather than designer collections. Rockabilly enthusiasts in leather jackets and pompadours occupy one section of the street. New Wave kids in asymmetric haircuts and black cotton clothing occupy another. The zones are internally consistent and externally identifiable: a spatial grammar of subcultural affiliation.\n\nThe relationship between Harajuku street fashion and the bubble economy in 1985 is indirect but real. The increasing prosperity of the surrounding society creates conditions in which visible self-expression through appearance is more socially tolerable than in earlier decades of Japanese economic development, when conformity was a professional and social requirement. The rising generation entering adolescence in 1985 has grown up in a Japan where consumption is itself a form of identity, and they extend this logic to their dress: not merely consuming brand products but assembling identities from a wider range of sources, including secondhand clothing markets, DIY modifications, and subcultural references invisible to their parents' generation. The street fashion subcultures are partly a response to the consumer abundance the bubble is creating and partly a refusal of the brand-logic that defines mainstream bubble consumption.\n\nThe documentation of Harajuku street fashion by magazines including Anan, Non-No, and street-specific publications creates a feedback loop between street invention and commercial production. Stylists sourcing looks for editorial shoots come to Harajuku; A-and-R executives and fashion directors observe what the street generates before markets are identified. The fashion that emerges from the street in Harajuku in 1985 will influence European and American designers who encounter it through fashion press. The subcultures that will define Japanese street fashion internationally through the 1990s are finding their forms here.",
