        title: "The Bubble Interior",
        body: "The magazines educating Japanese consumers in interior design in 1986 are not neutral reporters of existing taste. They are manufacturers of aspiration, and the aspiration they manufacture is specific: the globally sophisticated urban apartment, furnished with imported contemporary pieces, organized by a coherent design concept, treating domestic space as a statement of cultural identity. Brutus and equivalent publications are running spreads in which the apartment's identity communicates its occupant's sophistication to anyone who enters. The room is a social performance space, and design is the script.\n\nThe specific aesthetic promoted by design media in 1986 has identifiable European coordinates. Italian Memphis Group furniture — the movement founded by Ettore Sottsass in Milan in 1981, characterized by bright colors, geometric patterns, and deliberate rejection of conventional good taste — appears in several editorial spreads as the design language that signals avant-garde awareness. The Cassina Italia catalog introduces Japanese urban consumers to pieces by Le Corbusier (the LC2 armchair, manufactured by Cassina under license), Charlotte Perriand, and contemporary Italian designers. A Thonet bentwood chair or a Charles and Ray Eames lounge chair in a Tokyo apartment in 1986 communicates international design literacy as precisely as a Comme des Garçons jacket does on the street.\n\nThe consumer electronics component of the aspirational interior is significant and specifically Japanese. Nakamichi cassette decks, Technics turntables, Onkyo integrated amplifiers, and Pioneer CD players are not merely functional audio equipment; they are aesthetic objects whose presence in the living space communicates investment in quality and attention to the listening experience. Sony's Walkman has created a generation comfortable with portable audio; the home system is its stationary counterpart, displayed openly rather than concealed in a cabinet. The stereo equipment as design object gives consumer electronics manufacturers a visual presence in the aspirational interior that traditional home furnishings companies need to respond to. The interior of 1986 is a designed space integrating furniture, electronics, and objects into a coherent aesthetic statement.",
