        body: "The Japanese resort architecture of 1987 represents one of the most unusual commissions in twentieth-century building history: clients with surplus capital, no traditional constraints on aesthetic ambition, and a willingness to treat construction budgets as flexible that architects working elsewhere in the world found extraordinary. The Seibu Saison Group's expansion of Prince Hotel properties — ski resort hotels in Naeba (Niigata), Karuizawa, and Shiga Kogen — and the development of new coastal and island resort facilities by Recruit, JAL Hotels, and independent resort operators create a national construction program that employs Japan's most ambitious architects on projects of unusual scale and creative latitude.\n\nKisho Kurokawa — a founder of the Metabolism movement of the 1960s, which proposed replacing static urban infrastructure with dynamic, replaceable architectural systems inspired by biological growth — receives in 1987 a commission for the Nagoya City Art Museum (opened 1988) and is working on the Pacific Tower in Paris (completed 1992). His career trajectory through the late 1980s reflects a broader pattern: the generation of Japanese architects whose theoretical work gained international recognition in the 1960s and 1970s is now receiving commissions large enough to test their ideas at scale. Fumihiko Maki, who will win the Pritzker Prize in 1993, receives several institutional commissions in this period. Tadao Ando completes his Church on the Water in Hokkaido (1988) and Church of the Light in Osaka (1989) — projects whose budgets would have been impossible in less prosperous periods.\n\nThe landscape consequence of this building program is visible in the topography of Japanese mountain and coastal regions. Ski complexes at Naeba, Hakuba, and Shiga Kogen are expanded to accommodate corporate entertainment and premium leisure at a scale the Japanese skiing market of the 1970s could not have supported. The buildings are designed for a vocabulary of luxury — glass curtain walls, imported stone cladding, dramatic atrium lobbies — that signals prosperity to visitors. The architecture's financial logic is sound in 1987: property values supporting the corporate entertainment culture that fills these hotels are rising, and the aspiration to a resort weekend is spreading through a demographic large enough to fill the rooms. The hotels will become balance sheet problems by 1992. In 1987 they are dreams being built.",
