        title: "The Policy Tightening Begins",
        body: "The Bank of Japan's decision to begin raising rates in May 1989 reflects a belated recognition that the asset price inflation of the preceding four years has created conditions that low interest rates cannot continue to support. The official discourse focuses on domestic inflation — consumer prices had been rising modestly in 1989 — but the real concern within the BOJ is the equity and real estate markets, whose valuation levels had become a subject of serious internal analysis. Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita, who had maintained the 2.5% rate through the entirety of his tenure, is replaced in December 1989 by Yasushi Mieno, who will conduct the tightening with a speed and determination that exceed what the bubble required to deflate.\n\nThe rate sequence from May 1989 onward is rapid. The official discount rate moves from 2.5% to 3.25% on May 31, 1989; to 3.75% on October 11; and to 4.25% on December 25 — three increases in seven months. The increases continue into 1990: to 5.25% on March 20, 1990, and to 6.0% on August 30, 1990. The full tightening cycle moves the official rate from 2.5% to 6.0% in fifteen months — a 350 basis point increase at a speed that gives the economy minimal time to adjust. For comparison, the US Federal Reserve's tightening cycles that caused recessions typically proceeded at half this pace.\n\nThe tightening's logic is defensible and its execution is debatable. The asset bubble needed to be deflated; the question was whether a controlled deflation was achievable at any speed. The BOJ's defenders argue that only rapid tightening could break the expectations of continued appreciation that were sustaining valuations. The critics argue that the rapid tightening, by removing the cheap money that was sustaining both asset prices and corporate earnings simultaneously, guaranteed that the asset price decline would be accompanied by an economic contraction severe enough to impair the banking system's capacity to absorb the losses. Both arguments have merit. What is clear is that the combination of four years of excessive looseness followed by fifteen months of aggressive tightening is among the least effective monetary policy configurations available.",
