        title: "Land Price Peak",
        body: "Japanese land prices reach their historical maximum in late 1989 and early 1990, with commercial land in the most desirable districts of Tokyo trading at prices that represent perhaps the most extreme departure from fundamental value in the recorded history of real estate markets. The Japan Real Estate Institute's survey of commercial land in Tokyo's six central wards shows values that imply Japan's entire territory — approximately 377,000 square kilometers — worth somewhere between $15 and $20 trillion, against the United States' 9.6 million square kilometers valued at around $4 trillion at comparable per-square-meter rates. The comparison captures the magnitude of the divergence from any plausible productive use calculation.\n\nThe residential dimension of the peak is equally extreme. In 1989, the Land Agency's annual survey shows average land prices in Tokyo's metropolitan area at levels that would require a household earning the median income to spend its entire gross income for approximately 10–12 years to purchase a modest apartment with the land beneath it. Price-to-income ratios in central Tokyo exceed 20x, compared to 5–7x in London and New York in the same period. The hundred-year mortgage — in which the principal is expected to be inherited along with the property — is a financial product that leading Japanese banks are actively offering, representing the institutional acknowledgment that current land prices are sustainable only if they continue rising indefinitely.\n\nThe Land Agency's official survey methodology contributes to the late recognition of the peak's passing. Official land price assessments (kojichika) are conducted annually as of January 1 of each year and published in the spring. They measure prices for a specific set of benchmark plots rather than actual transaction prices, and the assessment process tends to lag market movements. The official survey published in spring 1991 (measuring January 1991 prices) shows modest declines in some Tokyo commercial districts — the first recorded declines in the postwar era. By that point, the actual transaction market has been weakening for months. The official statistic that proves the peak was in 1989–1990 is available only in 1991.",
