        title: "The Consumer Economy at Its Peak",
        body: "Japanese consumer spending in 1989 reaches its real historical maximum across the categories that define bubble-era daily life. Department store sales exceed 15 trillion yen annually. The number of Japanese citizens traveling abroad reaches approximately 9.6 million, triple the figure from 1985. New automobile registrations hit 7.8 million units. Household spending on dining out, entertainment, and leisure activities sets records in each category. The macroeconomic conditions enabling this consumption will not recombine in this configuration: full employment (unemployment at 2.3%), rising nominal wages, consumer price inflation low enough to preserve real wage growth, asset values producing a sustained wealth effect, and consumer credit cheap enough to fund the gap between income and aspiration.\n\nReal GDP growth in 1989 is approximately 5.4%, driven substantially by domestic consumption rather than net exports — exactly the rebalancing that the Maekawa Report had called for and that the interest rate cuts were theoretically intended to produce. The Plaza Accord and the subsequent rate cuts were intended to reduce Japan's current account surplus and expand domestic demand; in 1989, they have demonstrably succeeded on both metrics. By the strict measurement of the Maekawa Report's objectives, 1989 is the year the policy worked. The working of the policy has, simultaneously, produced an asset bubble that will require a decade of contraction to resolve.\n\nThe social texture of peak consumption in 1989 is worth noting because it will not return. The combination of disposable income, confidence, and social infrastructure for spending — the karaoke boxes, the resort hotels, the department store event calendar, the expense account restaurant culture — creates a specific urban Japanese experience that is not reproducible at lower income levels or lower confidence levels. The society that exists in 1989 Tokyo is prosperous, busy, somewhat anxious about housing costs, mostly unworried about employment, and culturally rich in the specific ways that prosperity without obvious purpose tends to produce. Its members will spend decades afterward looking back on it: first as a golden age, then as a cautionary tale, then, with enough distance, as both simultaneously.",
