        title: "The Nikkei Falls by Half",
        body: "The Nikkei's 1990 decline is the most severe single-year contraction in a major equity index since the early phases of the Great Depression. From the December 29, 1989 close of 38,915, the index falls to approximately 23,848 by December 31, 1990 — a 38.7% decline in a single calendar year. The intra-year low is reached on October 1, 1990, when the index touches 20,221 — a 48% decline from the peak within ten months. These are not the numbers of a correction; they are the numbers of a market that has discovered its valuations were wrong by approximately half and is adjusting accordingly. The speed of the adjustment reflects the sharpness of the monetary tightening that triggered it: the Bank of Japan raised the official discount rate from 2.5% to 6.0% in fifteen months, and the equity market incorporated this shift in information with equally rapid arithmetic.\n\nThe market's sectoral composition shapes the decline's damage distribution. The financial sector — banks, insurance companies, securities firms — suffers the largest absolute losses because these institutions hold the most equity exposure, both in their own investment portfolios and as collateral against loans. Nomura Securities, the world's largest securities company by assets in the late 1980s, sees its market capitalization fall by more than 60% over the year. City banks — Sumitomo, Fuji, Dai-Ichi Kangyo, Mitsui, Mitsubishi — whose equity portfolios had appreciated to represent significant fractions of their capital bases, find their reported capital ratios deteriorating as the appreciation reverses. The international bank capital adequacy framework (the Basel Accord, agreed in 1988) requires Japanese banks to maintain 8% capital adequacy ratios partially satisfied through unrealized equity gains; those gains are disappearing.\n\nThe real economy's connection to the equity market operates through channels that are ultimately more consequential than the financial sector's immediate losses. Corporate zaitech losses reverse the non-operating income that had inflated reported earnings through the mid-to-late 1980s. The corporate sector's transition from apparent profitability to apparent unprofitability happens within a single accounting year for many large companies. Investment plans predicated on sustained earnings and continued asset appreciation are revised. Hiring, capital expenditure, and overseas expansion plans are reconsidered. The equity market's collapse transmits to the real economy through corporate balance sheets, and the real economy's deterioration transmits back to the equity market through earnings expectations. The loop that amplified the upswing now amplifies the downswing.",
