        title: "Political Paralysis",
        body: "The political system that governs Japan's response to the bubble collapse is structurally ill-suited to the task. The Liberal Democratic Party, which has held continuous government power since 1955, derives its electoral coalition from the constituencies that benefited most from the bubble: large corporations, construction interests, financial institutions, and the older homeowning demographic whose paper wealth appreciated through the late 1980s. The acknowledgment that the bubble was a policy failure and that its consequences require structural adjustment — to corporate governance, to banking regulation, to land use policy, to lifetime employment conventions — is an acknowledgment that the LDP's policy coalition made choices whose consequences are now being borne by people outside that coalition. The political system is not designed to make this acknowledgment willingly.\n\nThe administrative guidance system, which had organized Japan's postwar economic management with considerable effectiveness, is also poorly configured for crisis response. The guidance system works through consensus: Ministry of Finance officials, Bank of Japan officials, and major financial institutions develop shared understandings of appropriate behavior and implement them without legislative process. The system is efficient when the parties share interests and when the direction of guidance is clear. In 1990 the interests are divergent and the direction of appropriate guidance is genuinely uncertain. The guidance system produces inaction when action is needed.\n\nBetween 1989 and 1993, Japan has five Prime Ministers: Noboru Takeshita (resigned April 1989 over the Recruit corruption scandal), Sosuke Uno (resigned August 1989 over personal scandal), Toshiki Kaifu (served August 1989 to November 1991), Kiichi Miyazawa (served November 1991 to August 1993), and Morihiro Hosokawa (the first non-LDP Prime Minister since 1955, took office August 1993). The rapid turnover reflects the instability of the LDP coalition under electoral and corruption pressure, not a genuine alternation of economic vision. None of the five administrations produces a comprehensive response to the banking crisis. The absence of a comprehensive response is itself a policy choice, made repeatedly across five administrations, that extends the economic damage of the bubble's collapse by a decade.",
